    <title>Combined summary - Hardfork to fix difficulty drop algorithm</title>
    <updated>2023-06-11T04:21:30.902746+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2016-March/012489.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin developers are discussing the upcoming subsidy halving in July 2016 and the potential for a significant drop in mining rate, which could lead to longer block intervals and the block size limit being hit sooner than expected. To address this, they propose a hardfork to the difficulty adjustment algorithm so it can adapt quicker to such a drop in mining rate. However, there may be concerns about tinkering with Bitcoin's "economic contract." A possible solution is to adjust the economic parameter instead of the difficulty targeting mechanism. Regardless, demonstrating a good process for making decisions and separating meaningful underlying principles from implementation details is key to increasing confidence in the system.The discussion among Bitcoin developers focuses on potential solutions to the halving-difficulty-drop problem, which could lead to disastrous consequences for miners and users. One proposed emergency code suggests reducing the difficulty by a large factor, while another proposes using CLTV locked outputs to add an additional layer of security. There is also a debate about the possibility of a hard-fork to fix the difficulty drop algorithm and the predictability of inflation in Bitcoin. The success of Bitcoin has led to discussions about the creation of a new Bitcoin or an altcoin with a 22-million-coin limit and a smooth inflation schedule. Some developers suggest that altering the predictability of inflation could make it unpredictable and create uncertainty. Lastly, there is a suggestion of using the critically damped harmonic oscillator as a solution for varying hash rates.Bitcoin developers have been discussing the predictability of Bitcoin's inflation model and the impact on investments. Eric Voskuil suggested that all capital investments are based on expectations of future returns, which can be factored in perfectly to make inflation a cost, not a tax. Peter Todd believes that hard forks constitute an attack and suggests creating an altcoin with a 22-million-coin limit and an inflation schedule with smooth drops. Luke Dashjr proposed adjusting the reward schedule to alleviate concerns about the upcoming subsidy halving in July. Dashjr also suggests a hard fork for the difficulty adjustment algorithm to adapt quicker to a significant drop in mining rate. Developers also discussed the challenges of accurately measuring the hashrate in Bitcoin, and the need for emergency code to lower the difficulty by a large factor if necessary. Gregory Maxwell argued against dynamically adjusting the difficulty of Bitcoin mining, while Paul suggested that miners should invest in hardware closer to the halving. The discussion also touched on the possibility of creating a new Bitcoin and using a number smaller than 2016 as a retarget interval for Bitcoin. Inflation is considered a cost based on expectations of future returns, and removing predictability would make it unpredictable.The upcoming subsidy halving in July 2016 has raised concerns that a significant number of miners could drop off the network, leading to a longer block interval and a higher per-block transaction volume. To alleviate this risk, a hardfork to the difficulty adjustment algorithm has been proposed by Luke Dashjr so it can adapt quicker to such a significant drop in mining rate. BtcDrak has well-tested code for this in his altcoin, which could be ready in time to be deployed alongside SegWit. In addition, there are discussions about changing futures to smooth out the Bitcoin block reward halving, which occurs every 210,000 blocks. However, some argue that changing these futures would punish those who have planned properly and create unpredictability. There is also discussion on accurately measuring the hashrate in Bitcoin as well as the potential for a non-trivial number of miners to drop off the network in July 2016 due to the subsidy halving.Bitcoin miners have invested heavily in the industry with hash rates increasing by almos